  "text": "SASL mechanism configuration validation in Apache Kafka at broker startup occurs across multiple Java source files. The validation process is orchestrated through a chain of initialization calls that ensure all SASL mechanisms are properly configured.\n\n**Core Validation Flow:**\n\n1. **Enabled Mechanisms Validation (ChannelBuilders.java:137-140)**: When the broker starts up in server mode with SASL_SSL or SASL_PLAINTEXT security protocol, ChannelBuilders.create() retrieves the sasl.enabled.mechanisms configuration from BrokerSecurityConfigs and iterates through each enabled mechanism to load corresponding JAAS contexts.\n\n2. **JAAS Configuration Presence Check (JaasContext.java:65-157)**: The loadServerContext() method checks for presence of JAAS configuration. For each mechanism, it looks for mechanism-specific dynamic JAAS config via SaslConfigs.SASL_JAAS_CONFIG with the mechanism name as prefix. If no dynamic config is found, it falls back to loading from the default JAAS configuration file. Critically, at lines 145-150, if no configuration is found, it throws an IllegalArgumentException indicating missing JAAS configuration.\n\n3. **JAAS Configuration Parsing (JaasConfig.java:52-122)**: The JaasConfig class parses JAAS configuration in the standard format and validates:\n   - That login modules are specified (line 66)\n   - That exactly one login module is present (lines 97-98)\n   - That control flags are valid (lines 83-105: REQUIRED, REQUISITE, SUFFICIENT, OPTIONAL)\n   - That all options have values (lines 115-116)\n   - That entries are properly terminated with semicolons (line 120)\n\n4. **Server Authenticator Initialization (SaslServerAuthenticator.java:178-189)**: During initialization, SaslServerAuthenticator validates:\n   - That sasl.enabled.mechanisms is not empty (lines 179-180)\n   - That callback handlers are registered for each enabled mechanism (lines 183-184)\n   - That subjects exist for each mechanism (lines 185-186)\n\n5. **Mechanism-Specific Callback Handler Setup (SaslChannelBuilder.java:createServerCallbackHandlers)**: The SaslChannelBuilder creates appropriate callback handlers based on the mechanism type:\n   - For PLAIN mechanism: PlainServerCallbackHandler validates user credentials from JAAS config\n   - For SCRAM mechanisms (SCRAM-SHA-256, SCRAM-SHA-512): ScramServerCallbackHandler validates SCRAM credentials from the credential cache\n   - For OAUTHBEARER: OAuthBearerUnsecuredValidatorCallbackHandler or a custom OAuthBearerValidatorCallbackHandler\n   - For GSSAPI/Kerberos: Default SaslServerCallbackHandler with KerberosShortNamer for principal mapping (lines 155-165)\n\n6. **OAUTHBEARER Configuration Validation (BrokerJwtValidator.java:107-139)**: When OAUTHBEARER is enabled, BrokerJwtValidator.configure() validates:\n   - SASL_OAUTHBEARER_CLOCK_SKEW_SECONDS (optional)\n   - SASL_OAUTHBEARER_EXPECTED_ISSUER (optional)\n   - SASL_OAUTHBEARER_SCOPE_CLAIM_NAME (required)\n   - SASL_OAUTHBEARER_SUB_CLAIM_NAME (required)\n   - Verification key resolver configuration\n\n7. **SCRAM Credential Validation (ScramControlManager.java:284-322)**: The ScramControlManager validates SCRAM credentials through validateUpsertion() and validateScramUsernameAndMechanism() methods, checking for valid mechanism types and credential iteration bounds.\n\n**Configuration Files Referenced:**\n\n- BrokerSecurityConfigs.java defines SASL_ENABLED_MECHANISMS_CONFIG (line 97), SASL_SERVER_CALLBACK_HANDLER_CLASS_CONFIG, and mechanism-specific OAUTHBEARER configuration options\n- SaslConfigs.java defines all SASL mechanism configuration properties including SASL_JAAS_CONFIG and mechanism-specific options\n\nThe validation ensures that only configured and supported SASL mechanisms can be used, their JAAS configurations are properly formatted and present, callback handlers are available for each mechanism, and mechanism-specific configurations meet requirements before the broker accepts client connections."
